A series of batch-mode CDI experiments were carried out on BOC and PDA-BOC electrodes (Fig. S6) to investigate the ability to treat brackish water with different concentrations, as well as the function mechanism of its functional groups. All electrodes are immersed in 80 °C NaCl solution in advance under a vacuum oven to remove air bubbles within the electrodes. When applying a voltage (1.4 V, Fig. 5
                     A), the conductivity of the solution with BOC and PDA-BOC electrodes all decreases rapidly, which proves their good ion adsorption capacity. However, from Equ.4, the SAC of PDA-BOC and BOC (Fig. S7) reached 17.48 mg g−1 and 11.11 mg g−1, respectively. This can be ascribed to the enhancement of ion adsorption capacity by interfacial modification. Theoretically, due to the hard-soft interaction principle [46], hard acid (Na+) tends to interact with B, O-containing functional groups through metal ligand bonds to achieve ion adsorption. At the same time, the nitrogenous functional groups on PDA will also adsorb a large amount of Na+. Therefore, the desalination speed of PDA-BOC electrode is obviously much faster than that of BOC electrode. The adsorption capacity is also correspondingly stronger, consistent with the previous capacitance test results. Under different applied voltages (1.0 V ∼ 1.6 V), the concentration of salt solution lowered rapidly in the first 15 min, and reached the adsorption equilibrium in about 25 min. At 1.0 V, 1.2 V, 1.4 V and 1.6 V (Fig. 5B), the SAC values are calculated as 7.69 mg g−1, 12.26 mg g−1, 17.48 mg g−1, and 23.07 mg g−1, respectively. Obviously, the greater the applied voltage, the stronger the salt adsorption capacity of the material. Explained from the perspective of the EDLC mechanism, the electrodes will carry stronger positive and negative charges at high voltages. To achieve charge balance, more salt ions are enriched at the interface. Ragone diagram of the PDA-BOC electrode (Fig. 5D) also proves that the adsorption capacity and desalination rate were improved at high voltage. When adsorption saturated, ions will be released from the electrode after the voltage is withdrawn or converted into a negative voltage, which is deemed as the electrode regeneration process. In addition, the process can recover some of the electrical energy used in the desalination process, allowing LED bulbs to be successfully lit during electrode regeneration process of adsorbing saturation at high voltage (Fig. S8). This phenomenon proves that CDI is a low-energy, environmentally friendly desalination technology. The regeneration stability of PDA-BOC was tested in an applied electric field of 1.2 V (Fig. 4E). PDA-BOC maintains an adsorption capacity of more than 92 % after up to 30 cycles continuous work (Fig. 5E), showing desirable cyclic stability. At the same time, with the gradual increment of the applied voltage, the electrical adsorption capacity and charging efficiency of PDA-BOC change accordingly (Fig. 5F), highlighting that high voltage is conducive to improving the CDI electrical adsorption capacity of materials once again. As the cell voltage rising, the reduced charge efficiency (0.70 to 0.51) may be attributed to side reactions and ion expulsion. Furthermore, the test results of CDI have certain advantages compared with the reported works (Table 1
                     ).
